  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Monitoring the impact of HIV education through football coaching</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">National HIV rates in Kenya are estimated to be around 6%, but young women in Nairobi&#x2019;s slums are thought to be up to four times as vulnerable as young men, not least because 24% report their first sexual encounter was forced. Tackle Africa is already supporting local organisation, Bravilian Queens Association, to deliver HIV education for girls through football, but they are finding it challenging to monitor and evaluate the impact of their activities effectively, particularly the contribution they are making to significant positive behaviour change amongst girls and young people. This Tactical Planning grant will enable the applicant to develop, implement and test a number of simple, qualitative monitoring and evaluation tools to assess the needs of vulnerable young girls in Nairobi&#x2019;s slums; monitor changes in their attitudes and behaviour; adapt and strengthen the organisation&#x2019;s HIV education football coaching drills according to their needs; and build the capacity of both the local partner and UK organisation in monitoring and evaluation.</narrative>
  </description>
